 came under pressure from demands of disclosure in the name of public health. Maehle structures his study around three representative questions of the time that remain salient today: Do physicians have a privilege to refuse court orders to reveal confidential patient details? Is there a medical duty to report illegal procedures to the authorities? Should doctors breach confidentiality in order to prevent the spread of disease? Considering these debates through a unique historical perspective, Contesting Medical Confidentiality illuminates the ethical issues and potentially grave consequences that continue to stir up public debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConfidential communicationsxPhysiciansxHistoryy19th century. 0aConfidential communicationsxPhysiciansxHistoryy20th century. 0aConfidential communicationsxPhysicianszGermanyxHistory. 0aConfidential communicationsxPhysicianszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aConfidential communicationsxPhysicianszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPhysiciansxProfessional ethics. 0aPrivacy, Right ofxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  aBritain.  aGermany.  aUnited States.  aabortion.  amedical confidentiality.  amedical privilege.  amedical secrecy.  apatient information.  aprivacy.  avenereal diseases.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022640482040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226404967423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226404967/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles